Fix RTCP SR timestamp base mismatch with RTP packets

In OnDemandServerMediaSubsession::startStream(), the initial RTCP
Sender Report was sent (via startPlaying -> sendReport) before
presetNextTimestamp() updated fTimestampBase. This caused the SR's
RTP timestamp to use the original random base while all subsequent
RTP packets used the preset base, producing a broken NTP-to-RTP
mapping. Clients using the SR for synchronization (e.g. ffmpeg over
UDP) would compute wildly incorrect PTS values.

Move presetNextTimestamp() before startPlaying() so the initial SR
and RTP packets share the same timestamp domain.

--- a/liveMedia/OnDemandServerMediaSubsession.cpp	2026-03-20 08:31:53.211231356 -0400
+++ b/liveMedia/OnDemandServerMediaSubsession.cpp	2026-03-20 08:31:53.213848817 -0400
@@ -248,13 +248,18 @@
   Destinations* destinations
     = (Destinations*)(fDestinationsHashTable->Lookup((char const*)clientSessionId));
   if (streamState != NULL) {
+    RTPSink* rtpSink = streamState->rtpSink(); // alias
+    if (rtpSink != NULL) {
+      // Preset the RTP timestamp before startPlaying() so that the
+      // initial RTCP SR (sent inside startPlaying) uses the correct
+      // timestamp base, matching subsequent RTP packet timestamps.
+      rtpTimestamp = rtpSink->presetNextTimestamp();
+    }
     streamState->startPlaying(destinations, clientSessionId,
 			      rtcpRRHandler, rtcpRRHandlerClientData,
 			      serverRequestAlternativeByteHandler, serverRequestAlternativeByteHandlerClientData);
-    RTPSink* rtpSink = streamState->rtpSink(); // alias
     if (rtpSink != NULL) {
       rtpSeqNum = rtpSink->currentSeqNo();
-      rtpTimestamp = rtpSink->presetNextTimestamp();
     }
   }
 }
